Met with Helen Macneil, CEO of Glasgow Council for Voluntary Services (GCVS), Mary Sinclair, Information Manager at GCVS, Gareth Allen, Head Intra-Government Team, Scottish Government Third Sector Division, and Diane Kennedy, Evaluation Support Scotland (</gtr:impact><gtr:outcomeId>r-1701771534.70159652b681210</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:partOfOfficialScheme>false</gtr:partOfOfficialScheme><gtr:primaryAudience>Policymakers/Parliamentarians</gtr:primaryAudience><gtr:year>2012</gtr:year></gtr:disseminationOutput></gtr:disseminationOutputs><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs/><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs/><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:keyFindingsOutput><gtr:description>The main findings of the project are as follows:



? There are two particular challenges in quantifying the relationship between provision of preventative services and use of formal health and social care services. The first is specification: standardised measures need to be developed which can potentially reflect the value of preventative service provision. The literature suggests that these are currently specified on a case-by-case basis. The second challenge is attribution: establishing how much of the variation in formal service use is due to using preventative services rather than other factors. 



? Quantifying relationships becomes increasingly complex when considering preventative services in aggregate. Data collection becomes more difficult, attribution is problematic and frequently contested, and findings can appear contradictory. For example, the evaluation of the Department of Health-funded 'Partnership for Older People Projects' (PoPP) initiative in England by PSSRU (2009) suggested reductions in hospital stays and outpatient services use with consequent cost savings, whilst the analysis of 8 projects within PoPP by Steventon et al (2011) found no reduction in emergency hospital use. 



? Existing data sources on Scottish third sector preventative service provision are limited and detailed data needed for modelling are lacking. Data collection is expensive, and with more than 45,000 organisations the Scottish third sector is vast. Targeted one-off data collections (e.g. GCVS' 'Reshaping Care for Older People Glasgow Third Sector Mapping' dataset) and regular but relatively small-scale general collections (e.g. SCVO's biannual Panel Survey) are available, but in order to better understand the contribution of preventative services provided by the third sector to formal services use a more targeted, comprehensive and regular data collection is required.



? An examination of more recently adopted evaluation methodologies such as Social Return on Investment (SROI) suggests that data collected by third sector organisations carrying out such evaluations might provide a potentially useful source of data going forward. However, those evaluation methodologies which would produce the best data are time-consuming, can be expensive, and may not meet the requirements of smaller organisations. As a result they are not yet widely used across the Scottish third sector. In addition problems with specification would remain as such evaluations do not incorporate standard specifications of measures relevant to this purpose.



? Models of future care provision need to take into account both availability/accessibility and how older people make choices about service use. The impact of individuals' knowledge of and subjective choices regarding the use (or non-use) of different services is not well known, and is likely to mediate the relationship between preventative service provision and formal service use in a given area.</gtr:description><gtr:id>1B29737D-E23E-451F-83DB-C82BEB8C7830</gtr:id><gtr:outcomeId>r-6359698368.571418b2f348fc</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:sectors><gtr:sector>Digital/Communication/Information Technologies (including Software)</gtr:sector></gtr:sectors></gtr:keyFindingsOutput><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs/><gtr:researchMaterialOutputs/><gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutputs/><gtr:spinOutOutputs/></gtr:output><gtr:publications/><gtr:identifiers><gtr:identifier type="RES">RES-173-27-0233</gtr:identifier><gtr:identifier type="RCUK">ES/I030182/1</gtr:identifier></gtr:identifiers><gtr:healthCategories/><gtr:researchActivities/><gtr:researchSubjects><gtr:researchSubject><gtr:id>7D5D2DB2-0A64-42AF-A644-5F541B832A29</gtr:id><gtr:percentage>0</gtr:percentage><gtr:text>Economics</gtr:text></gtr:researchSubject><gtr:researchSubject><gtr:id>12179D88-04B3-47E9-89E1-B5EE8F895227</gtr:id><gtr:percentage>0</gtr:percentage><gtr:text>Social Policy</gtr:text></gtr:researchSubject><gtr:researchSubject><gtr:id>F0322ED6-113F-4530-BA5E-562216587E68</gtr:id><gtr:percentage>0</gtr:percentage><gtr:text>Sociology</gtr:text></gtr:researchSubject></gtr:researchSubjects><gtr:researchTopics><gtr:researchTopic><gtr:id>7D5D2DB2-0A64-42AF-A644-5F541B832A29</gtr:id><gtr:percentage>0</gtr:percentage><gtr:text>Economics</gtr:text></gtr:researchTopic><gtr:researchTopic><gtr:id>12179D88-04B3-47E9-89E1-B5EE8F895227</gtr:id><gtr:percentage>0</gtr:percentage><gtr:text>Social Policy</gtr:text></gtr:researchTopic><gtr:researchTopic><gtr:i